Product name: Rare Antique Miniature Georgian Lover's Eye Mourning Locket, circa 1820
Description:
Towards the end of the 18th Century, there was a very brief fashion for one of the most secretive and romantic jewelry gifts...'lover's eye' jewelry. Crafty lovers would present miniature hand painted eye's to each other, in the form of brooches, rings and lockets, so that they could worn with impunity - under the impression that no one else would recognize it and they could keep their love a secret. As you can imagine, these tokens are now immensely scarce and extremely sought after!
Made around 1820, this little pendant tests around 15 carat gold and is set to the front with a border of French Jet and pearls around a tiny locket glass. And inside that glass is hand painted miniature eye. Most likely painted on ivory (the common practice of the time), the eye is looking directly at the beholder. This eye was probably painted earlier than the locket, around 1780/90. We believe it was probably trimmed down from a portrait by a heartbroken husband, and inserted into this locket to remember his dear wife, some time in the 19th Century. It measures only 0.68 inches diameter, and the eye itself is 0.29 inches diameter.
Worn to remember and honor his wife, this sweet little marriage of eye and locket would have been a reminder of their love and his loss - the most romantic and painful emotions all humans have felt throughout the centuries. It leans towards the fashion of mourning jewelry as well as the romantic sentimental era of the 'lover's eyes', and equally special in both ways. Whilst much smaller and not an original 'lover's eye', this token is still so rare and special, and is a must for any antique jewelry fan! 
Condition Notes: As expected for a painting over 200 years old, there is some fading & loss to the eye itself - this can be seen in the photographs. The natural pearls show some abrasions, but nothing detrimental to the piece. The bail is an old replacement, and there is some light denting to the reverse.

Product name: Antique Victorian Belle Epoque Fur Muff Gladstone Bag- Engraved Frame- Circa 1880- Steampunk Style
Description:
A fabulous antique Victorian Belle Epoque fur muff Gladstone style bag with a beautiful engraved frame and clasp dating from the 1880's.
The design is typical of the Belle Epoch, it features technology and style and must have cost a small fortune. It is this period that inspired the steampunk design that we see today.
The engraved frame is beautifully worked, the engraving is worked to the front, top and back of the frame and to the handle fittings as well. 
The bag opens by sliding the clasp to one side to reveal brown silk lining and a spacious bag. The back of the bag has an intergral muff worked into the design for keeping hands warm on cold Victorian mornings.
The bag is in extremely good condition with just some wear to the lining and to one side of the back of the bag as seen in the photos. It is by far the best example of this style of bag that I have seen yet.

Product name: Lavender Deodorant, Organic Shea Butter Deodorant, Arrowroot Deodorant
Description:
Almost all natural deodorant (except fragrance)! No aluminum......which is awesome because aluminum (the main ingredient for store bought deodorants) is hazardous for our health! This listing gets you one 2 oz jar of my deodorant. If you have super sensitive pits you can have the option for no baking soda! If you want it to be vegan, I can also omit the beeswax. Just use the option drop boxes to select "baking soda" or "no baking soda" and for "vegan" or "beeswax". My deodorants are made to order to ensure freshness. Coconut oil and organic unrefined shea butter helps with moisture and fights bacteria, arrowroot and clay helps absorb wetness. In hot weather your deodorant may become soft, just pop it in the fridge for a few minutes to harden again. 
When using a natural deodorant for the first time, it takes time for your body to adjust to your deodorant. This time period can be days or weeks, which you may sweat more and may need to apply more often to prevent stink. This is NOT an anti-perspirant. If a rash happens to develop, please discontinue use. 
To use, just swipe your finger to get about a dime size amount and rub into your pits. Wait a couple minutes for it to dry, then dress. 
Ingredients: arrowroot powder, coconut oil, organic unrefined shea butter, kaolin clay, baking soda*, beeswax*, fragrance.
* May be omitted upon request

Each flute is built with holes that have been traditionally burned into the flute 
and build from in two halves so that each cut of the wood was from the inside to the outside 
of the flute insuring a higher quality sound, all the Flutes I build have two chambers of air with the top (buffalo)
being the adjustment for sound (like a reed on a modern instrument would work),This part I personally carve into 
the bottom pice and tune not all Flutes sound alike some have deeper tones and other more softer tones, 
Every Flute I build has its own spiritual sound and is Tuned by my NATIVE HEART and played from your Heart.
Cedar Wood was Traditionally used to carve the flutes. Why? Cedar trees hold a special meaning. These trees have a shallow root system. In order to grow strong, their roots must intertwine with other Cedar tree roots for support, and to withstand adverse weathering conditions. This support system was meaningful to Native Americans. Just as the Cedar tree has a network of family support, so did the Indian Tribe. The Cedar tree has always represented the family, and like a Cedar tree, One was never Alone.
WHO ARE WE:
  OUR FAMILY STEPS ARE TRACED BACK TO CHIEF WASHAKIE AND THE BEAR RIVER MASSACRE, GREAT GRANDMOTHER WAS ONE OF THE FEW SURVIVORS OF THAT TERRIBLY ATTACK.  (SEEN IN THE PROFILE PHOTO) SHE WAS A GREAT BASKET BUILDER LIKE MANY SHOSHONE PEOPLE WERE. OUR FAMILY HAS MANY ARTISTIC TALENT, WE ARE KNOWLEDGABLE IN OUR HERITAGE AND KNOW WHO WE ARE, OVER 40 YEARS AGO WE OPENED UP AN INDIAN TRADING POST, WE PURCHASED HAND MADE ITEMS FROM OTHER FAMILY ARTISTS AND SOLD THEM TO HELP PROVIDE FOR THEIR FAMILY AND OURS. Product name: Cochineal Natural Dye | Red Fabric Dye | Yarn Dye | Natural Dyestuff | Eco Friendly Dye | Child Safe Dye | Scarlet Dye | Ancient Dye Carmine
Description:
Cochineal is a rare and precious dye made from a scale insect.  It is similar to other ancient natural dyes kermes and lac, and produces very similar colors. It makes lovely bright reds, pinks, and purples.
New to natural dyes?  The cochineal comes with complete instructions on how to use it!
Cochineal is an excellent dye for silk and wool, use 12 - 50% by weight, depending on how bright you want your color to be. 
Like many natural dyes, cochineal produces different tones depending on what fixer (mordant, metal salt) you use!
Alum (crimson red)
Tin (scarlet red)
Copper (violet)
Iron, used after (plum)
Chrome (lavenders) 
Our cochineal is of very high quality, and can be used to make the brightest of colors. It comes from Peru, where the cochineal is cultivated by traditional methods, outside, in the high Andes.
No bugs died to create this dye!  They are collected from the prickly pear cactus after they have already completed their natural life cycle.
This listing is for cochineal in two weights : 
1 oz packet (~ 28 grams)
4 oz packet (~ 113 grams)
If you'd like to purchase in bulk (1 pound or more), please let me know!  
An example of silk dyed with cochineal :
https://www.etsy.com/listing/495020779/crimson-red-silk-skein-naturally-dyed

Product name: Harris Tweed Cloche Hat - Multi Autumnal Colour Herringbbone, Women's Hat, Fabric Hat, Wool Hat
Description:
A wonderful womans cloche hat handmade from the most beautiful genuine *Harris tweed fabric in a stunning multi autumnal colour herringbone weave .  The hat is fully lined with a cotton fabric and a genuine Harris tweed label is sewn in for authenticity.  A decorative band and three handmade buttons in the same fabric finish the hat beautifully.
Made to order  
size small - will fit up to 21.5"
medium - will fit up to 22.5" 
large - will fit up to 23.5"
x large - will fit up to 24.5"
If you are unsure of your headsize then follow these simple steps to measure for size. Use a soft tape, start at the forehead working down towards the nape of the neck where a hat would naturally fall and then back up over the ear towards the forehead. Do this three times and take the average measurement, simple!
*Harris Tweed is the only handwoven fabric produced in commercial quantities. The yarn production process uses specially blended yarns produced to secret recipes and then warped up to exclusive designs before being sent to weavers’ homes to be handwoven by highly skilled weavers.
The cloth is then returned to the mill to be finished in a modern finishing plant to a very high standard. The next stage in the process is examination by the independent Harris Tweed Authority, before application of the famous Orb trademark which is ironed onto the fabric as the ultimate seal of approval..
Only then is it genuine, authenticated Harris Tweed. The Orb has served the industry well as a safeguard against imitations and is the oldest British trade mark in continuous use.
